snippet.textDisplay:
1. Please feed her wet kitten food in the morning and night. Leave out a dry kitten kibble in a separate dish for her to graze on all day; ideally high calorie or for pregnant/nursing cats. She seems pretty thin for a pregnant cat. Look for a food low in carbs. Meat should be the first few ingredients at least.
2. Please take her to a vet so they can recommend a more personalized diet for her. I am not sure for California, but veterinarians are considered essential in many states and taking her to a vet should be possible.
3. It's obvious you're very attached to her, but you really need to consider what kinds of dogs you have. You have huskies, those are extremely high prey dogs and notorious for not being cat friendly. If you plan to keep her I would start working with your dogs on slowly exposing them to cats right away. It is vital with high prey drive dogs that you socialize them as young as you can to small creatures. I would recommend a board certified behaviorist. I really hope it works out, but keep in mind you have four large prey driven dogs to consider. You can't keep her cooped up in a room.
